  "doi": "10.1042/bj20090732",
  "title": "Fluorine substitutions in an antigenic peptide selectively modulate T-cell receptor binding in a minimally perturbing manner.",
  "journal": "The Biochemical journal",
  "year": 2009,
  "authors": "Piepenbrink KH, Borbulevych OY, Sommese RF, Clemens J, Armstrong KM, Desmond C, Do P, Baker BM."
 },
 "executive_summary": "This study examined how fluorine substitutions in the HTLV-1 Tax(11-19) peptide presented on MHC selectively modulate recognition by two different Tax-specific TCRs (A6 and B7). Using crystallographic structures and structure-guided design, the authors found that fluorination enhanced binding by TCR A6 while weakening binding by TCR B7, with minimal perturbation to peptide structure. The selectivity arises from a \"polar hydrophobicity\" mechanism of fluorine's effect on TCR recognition rather than purely hydrophobic or electrostatic interactions. This approach of rational fluorine substitution offers a tool for enhancing TCR-peptide-MHC interactions in a discriminating manner, with potential applications in vaccine development and overcoming the inherent weak, fast kinetics that challenge structural studies of TCR recognition.",
